<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission from Action with Communities in Rural England (ACRE) (FDC21)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> from Action with Communities in Rural England (ACRE) (FDC21)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">1. Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Action with Communities in Rural England (ACRE) is the national umbrella for 38 rural community-led regeneration </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">organisations known as Rural Community Councils. ACRE itself was formed in 1987, but its members were created between 1920 and 2011, and so it </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">possesses vast experience across the entirety of rural England with regard to devolved decision-making processes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">ACRE is a charity and, together with the 38 Rural Community Councils, forms the ACRE Network.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.3</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">ACRE is co-financed by Defra to provid</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">e information on the impact of government policies in rural areas. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> The possibility of fiscal devolution to cities and city regions has potential impact on rural areas; we have noted disparities in how rural communities are served through existing devolved</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> structures (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">.g. Local Government, Local Enterprise Partnerships etc.) and wish to see all areas treated with equity. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.4</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Examples of the work of the ACRE Network can be found in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Making a Difference in rural communities throughout England</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> - published jo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">intly by ACRE and Defra in the autumn of 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Our response is brief, but we would be happy to share further information so as to support the work of the select committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We welcome the concept of fiscal devolution to cities and city </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">regions. Our network is built upon very local models of participatory democracy, and so we see the potential that this type involvement in decision-making can have in wider geographies.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We are particularly pleased to see that the Chair of the Communities </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">and Local Government Committee, Clive Betts MP, has recognised a need to identify how rural areas might be impacted by proposals for fiscal devolution to cities and city regions.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We would like to stress that rural areas are integral, and not peripheral, t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">o city regions.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Rural proofing is essential to helping ensure that city regions consider their rural geographies and that fair levels of devolved resource are allocated to these locations</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">. Performance management of devolution should include a ‘rurally awa</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">re’ component.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The concept of fiscal devolution to cities and city regions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">The ACRE Network is governed by, and serves, public, private and civil society organisations across rural England. The Network’s activity – primarily an enabling one </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">(providing information, training, consultancy, guidance and networking opportunities) – has a strong focus on participatory democracy, bringing public, private and civil society bodies together at a very local level (e.g. in a single village) to plan for t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">he socio-economic and environmental wellbeing of a particular geography. This is a form of government ‘by the people and for the people’ that should augment representative democratic structures such as Parish, District</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> / Borough</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">, Unitary and County Council</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">s.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> Our work in this field has included supporting:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">The creation of over 4,000 community-led plans (setting economic, social and environmental priorities at local level, and enabling the attraction and delivery of external funding to provide new services an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">d facilities)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">; usually with participation rates between 60 and 90% of the population</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Management of over 11,000 community-owned </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">facilities</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> (largely village halls, but also community-owned shops, pubs, transport operations etc.) These facilities support over 70,000 jobs in rural England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">In the first six months of the 2013/14 financial year alone t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">he work of the ACRE Network underpinned the o</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">pening of more than £40 million of affordable housing</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">, helped create 118 new businesses (and assisted a further 287, including village shops, to maintain their viability and / or improve performance) and provided over 9,000 people living in rural areas wi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">th access to health and social care services (keeping this number of people out of residential care saves around £180 million a year</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">). In addition, 2,886 village halls used the services of ACRE Network members: these venues represent an asset value of aro</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">und £2.1billion and are a space in which more than 20,000 jobs deliver goods and services</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.2</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We see, on a daily basis, the benefits of cross-sector working in tightly defined geographical areas. This means inclusive decision-making processes, drawing o</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">n a wide skills’ base, locally-tailored solutions to specific problems and even the ability to attract and generate further investment. The scaling-up of such an approach, to deliver on specific agendas, is something we welcome.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">4. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Rural impact</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">are particularly pleased to see that the Chair of the Communities and Local Government Committee, Clive Betts MP, has recognised a need to identify how rural areas might be impacted by proposals for fiscal devolution to cities and city regions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We are</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> co-financed by Defra to provide information on the impact of Government policies in rural areas. In the instance of a proposal such as the one considered here, impact can only be surmised</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> as there are many variables to be taken into account.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We know</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> from our own membership (i.e. 38 Rural Community Councils) that the importance of policy initiatives on rural areas varies greatly – as, indeed, is local investment targeted at community-led regeneration generally. Our figures suggested that, on a per hea</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">d of population basis, local public sector investment in our network can vary hugely – in 2012 we found an example variation of £0.19 </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">per head in one area</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> (e.g. Kent), but £3.80 in another (e.g. Central Bedfordshire</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">.) We know also by early work with Local</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> Enterprise Partnerships containing significant urban populations, that some (e.g. Coast to Capital) are very cognizant of rural economic growth – and how this contributes to a wide geography – and so are already investing in agendas such as affordable hou</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">sing and community-owned workspace</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Where an area (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">that might contain a city</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> has a major rural hinterland, that perhaps is recognised as a key contributor to the economy (or has its own economic challenges and a substantial rural population) then there are positive signs that devolved decision-making can be beneficial for rural ar</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">eas. We could cite the work of the New Anglia LEP as an example, or indeed various economic development initiatives (e.g. use of the LEADER mechanisms to support innovation in local business and community enterprise, broadband roll-out, multi-village neigh</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">bourhood planning)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">seen in Cumbria over the past decade.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.5</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Impact on rural areas might also be affected by the representational composition of structures created to oversee investment. Our network is involved in a number of structures designed to grow </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">the economy, but doing this by setting and delivering on local priorities. However, there is an inconsistent picture across the country, and in some places our members have not become part of structures – and this tends to reflect on the ‘political positio</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">n’ of either rural areas</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">, community-led regeneration</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> or civil society in relation to economic growth in those places. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Examples of our Network’s involvement in such structures (as at December 2013) is:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">4 on LEP Boards (representing 10% coverage)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">24 on LEP T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">hematic Working Groups or Sub-Committees (61% coverage)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">7 involved with Rural Growth Networks (100% coverage)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">5. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Rural areas are integral, and not peripheral, to city regions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Much of England’s rural land is devoted to production of energy (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">food), and this benefits the whole country. By necessity this energy production requires large amounts of land, and so settlements within it tend to be small – often meaning that it is more expensive to deliver specific services or run major businesses in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">rural areas. Much of our Network’s activity is targeted at alleviating the impacts of this: nobody should be disadvantaged because they live or work in a rural area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.2</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">However, rural areas often do miss out on major investment – or adequate means to add</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">ress market failure. Our network’s role is to provide the tools and expertise that allow rural communities to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">identify, articulate and address their needs. These needs do not exist in isolation but often struggle to be met because necessary investment is t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">argeted at urban areas where greater concentration of need exists (even if total figures for specific problems are less than in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">surrounding, but spread out, rural areas!) To this end we have worked with the Oxford Consultants for Social Inclusion (OCSI) to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> produce data sets</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> covering the rural share of deprivation, economy and other subjects across the entirety of England. We can generate reports at LEP, County Council, Clinical Commissioning, District Council, Parish and even individual place level. The ai</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">m is to demonstrate that any policy or investment decision will impact a specific cohort of the population living and / or working in a rural area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.3</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Rural areas are integral to city regions because the energy (e.g. food) produced </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">is also consumed in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">urban areas. P</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">eople working in cities may live in rural locations and there is much access to the countryside for leisure and recreational purposes. While spatial disadvantage arises in rural areas from the need to use land for agriculture, horticulture, f</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">orestry etc. – i.e. the land needed means small populations and less strong economies of scale for delivering services or operating certain types of business – the function of rural areas is to support the whole population. We see, therefore, that there is</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">interdependency</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> between rural and urban areas and thus the former is an integral part of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">any geography that is not purely urban in its confines.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">6. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Recommendation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">At this stage we have one recommendation to make: devolved fiscal responsibilities should be subject to rural-proofing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.2</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">We wish to see fair allocations of resource to rural areas, as opposed to an ability for devolved structures simply to invest in t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">hose places with the single greatest return on investment (thus compounding disadvantage elsewhere.) Where spend of public money is to come under greater control, then a means of attributing this to take into account rural population, land area and depriva</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">tion levels should be considered. Our experience is that great inconsistencies exist across the country in how rural areas are served through existing devolved power, and that a strong national framework needs to be in place as a ‘check and balance’ agains</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">t further disadvantaging some rural areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.3</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">Defra has produced various rural-proofing toolkits which might be used as a starting point for this process. We would be happy to help shape a sensible rural-proofing guide fit for the purposes of a fiscal de</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">volution to cities and city regions agenda.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> Based on English Rural Housing Association estimates of £150,000 build cost for each local needs house completed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> Based on figures set out in Office for Disability Issues (2007). </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Better Outcomes, Lower Costs: Implications for Health and Social Care Budgets of investment in Housing Adaptations, Improvements and Equipment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">: A review of the evidence. Heywood F and Turner</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> L. These estimate savings of more than £20,000 per client.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> ACRE (2009) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Rural Community Buildings in England 2009. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">ACRE, Cirencester. This report states that seven jobs underpinned by each village hall in England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> These figures deduced from Charity Com</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">mission returns against ONS-generated rural population figures; as such numbers are indicative.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> Further information available at </span><a href="http://www.rural-evidence.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">www.rural-evidence.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt"> </span></p></body></html>